This began shortly after Jeremy became the leader. Colleagues with whom I had previously thought I had similar political views began to expect that I would turn 180 degrees and adopt positions that I would never agree with, be it national security or the EU single market.
Every time I speak in public — and it doesn’t matter what I say — it’s followed by a tirade of attacks on social media with calls for revocation, condemnation of the center’s policies, I’m told that I shouldn’t be in the Labour Party.
And it’s not just my experience.
I know I’ve been more fortunate than some of my colleagues because the comments I’ve received are usually political.
I am delighted with the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who face daily streams of sexist or racist attacks, but never give up.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this political era is that levels of abuse have become the norm.
Jeremy Corbyn said last week that the Labour Party should nurture a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer such a broad church, and with each movement of “distrust” or changing the rules of selection the party narrows down.
Over the past two years, I have received a lot of advice. I have been urged not to stand up, not to speak out so loud that “all is well with me”.
That’s not why I came to politics.
I joined the Labour Party 32 years ago as a schoolboy, because my middle school class was literally falling apart because of a lack of attention from the Thatcher government, and since then I've been trying to improve the quality of public services for those most in need, whether it's a local councilor or a government minister.
I have never hidden my politics, including in the last election.
No one in Nottingham East was confused by my political views and disagreements with the current leadership.
For those who contributed to Friday’s events, I want to say only one thing: in a context where the country is moving towards a Brexit that will hurt households, businesses and public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
In fact, I have another message, not for the Nottingham Momentum, but for my constituents, as members of the Labour Party, and not: I am proud to serve you, and I promise that no threat to recall me and no political gain will prevent me from acting in accordance with what I consider to be the best interests of all of you.
