John Edward: knowledge of languages is a must for the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools maintain high standards of learning, and in 2018 they again received excellent exam results, complemented by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other fields.
These schools, which enroll more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, are represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SICs). They strive to provide the best level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further and higher education, their chosen career, as well as make them citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an individualized school curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject to choose from in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a person in a language they understand, they perceive it with their mind.
If you speak to her in her native language, she perceives it with her heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot use only English if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From the latest results of this year’s exams, we see that in independent schools, languages are leading in the rankings of subjects with the best grades.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages received a higher A score.
The data collected at 74 schools in the country showed that 72% of students received a higher A score in Chinese, and another 72% of those who study German, 69% of those who study French, and 63% of those who study Spanish also received an A.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland consider foreign languages to be vital skills that children and young people will no doubt need in the future.
Now languages as a subject of choice are taught in the same way as the subjects of NTIM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics), in the framework of independent school programs and in other institutions.
A 2014 survey by the British Employment and Skills Commission found that 17% of the reasons why employers can’t close vacancies are related to language skills shortages.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more promising positions require language proficiency, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of your chosen career, if someone has learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, because it is a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically gives a person who speaks several languages an advantage over competitors.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to support the conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people (15%).
That’s why investing in language teaching is important for today’s children.
Knowledge of several languages, especially those of developing countries, will provide children with a better chance of finding a full-time job.
In Scotland, each school will learn their own languages.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK from the 2020 perspective, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Regardless of your child’s interests in independent schools, it will always be possible to choose several languages to study with qualified teachers.
Scottish independent schools are trying to create an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills necessary to succeed no matter what the future holds for them.
Now it cannot be denied that in the international business environment languages continue to be vital for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be considered as “skills of international communication”.
Independent schools will continue to provide this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
