North Korea says it will not “under any circumstances” disarm unilaterally without trust
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the extension of sanctions deepens distrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country will in no way be able to give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual UN General Assembly that North Korea had taken “substantial goodwill measures” last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site and committing not to proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
"However, we do not see a corresponding reaction from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances we will in no way be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri repeated North Korea’s familiar complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, according to which North Korea would be rewarded for step-by-step steps, his statement proved important because it did not reject the unilateral denuclearization that Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first-ever summit between the incumbent U.S. President and North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim called for work on “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula” and Trump promised security guarantees to North Korea.
North Korea seeks a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first abandon nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal by force, and even opposes the ‘declaration of the end of the war,’” Ri said.
“To believe that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an impossible dream for those who don’t know us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions deepens our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader stressed at the UN earlier this week.
Instead, the minister drew attention to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: “If South Korea were on the side of denuclearization rather than the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not have gone to such a dead end.”
Despite this, Ri’s tone was sharply different from last year’s when he told the General Assembly that North Korea’s missile targeting the US mainland was inevitable after “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” who wants to commit suicide.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in taking disarmament measures, but said there was still a lot to be done and sanctions should remain in place until the denuclearization of North Korea.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not set a timeline for this: “It will take two years, three years or five months — it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “Enforcement of Security Council sanctions should continue vigorously and relentlessly until we see complete, definitive, confirmed denuclearization.”
The Security Council has unanimously increased sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to block funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear programs and ballistic missiles.
Pompeo met Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was unsuccessful.
He left Pyongyang in July and commented that progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea condemned him for “gangster demands.”
During a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea promised to dismantle the missile complex, as well as the nuclear complex, if the United States takes “appropriate measures”.
He said that, according to Kim, he needed “appropriate measures” are the security guarantees Trump promised in Singapore and steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has provided all of its students with more sleep. It is an attempt to combat the growing culture of steepness of learning all night after being refilled with caffeine.
The teacher found that the number one university students in the world are often uneducated when it comes to the very basics of how to take care of yourself.
Charles Chaisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Women’s Hospital, has developed a course that he believes is the first such course in the United States.
He decided to start the course after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
In the end, a girl approached him and said, “Why am I being told this now, in my final year?”
“She told me that no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
In the course, which was first introduced this year, students are explained the basics of how good sleep habits help to achieve academic and sports results, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of medical services at the university, said the university decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were seriously deprived of sleep for a week.
The hour-long course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one section, there is an image of a dorm room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, simulators and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, the impact of sleep deprivation on athletic performance, and the importance of sleep-related routines.
Another section tells participants how prolonged sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Next, the campus map with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not change the behavior of students instantly.
But we think they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know about the health effects of smoking,” Chaisler added.
A culture of pride for “wake up all night” still exists, he added, noting that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is growing.
Sufficient sleep of good quality should be the student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, even with weight gain, as sleep deprivation turns the brain into a hunger regime that causes constant physical hunger, he said.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Chaisler develop the course after enrolling in one of his other courses last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to create a new course for the entire campus.
The next step, he hopes, will be to appeal to all postgraduate students with a request to undergo a similar program of study before coming to a competitive institution.
Professor Chaisler advises students to put reminders to go to bed, as well as to put an alarm clock and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” that is emitted by electronic screens and LED lamps and can disrupt the circadian rhythm, leading to problems with falling asleep.
