Almanac: inventor of the Geiger counter
And now the page from our almanac "Sunday Morning": September 30, 1882, 136 years ago on this day, and the time is coming... in Germany was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactive radiation, an invention that eventually evolved into a device known as the Geiger counter.
Since then, the countable Geiger has become one of the key elements of science, as well as one of the key elements of pop culture, for example in the 1950 film The Coronado Bells with Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, who play dubious-looking cowboy scientists.
Man: “What is it?”
Rogers: “This is a Geiger counter used to find radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you wear these headphones, you can really hear how the radioactivity in minerals affects atoms.”
Evans: "Well, well, it's really cracking right now!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name continues to live on.
New cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to “see” malignant cells
A new cancer vaccine could teach the immune system to “see” malignant cells and kill them
Vaccine teaches immune system to recognize malignant cells that are part of treatment
The method involves the extraction of immune cells in the patient and their change in the laboratory
Then these cells are able to "see" the protein that is common to many types of cancer. Then these cells are again injected into the patient.
The trial vaccine shows promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
In one woman who received a vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells, ovarian cancer disappeared for more than 18 months.
The method involves removing the immune cells from the patient, changing them in the laboratory so that these cells can “see” the protein common to many cancers (HER2), and then re-injecting these cells to the patient.
Professor Jay Berzofsky of the National Cancer Institute in Bethesda, Maryland, said: “Our results show that we have received a very promising vaccine.”
“HER2 ‘stimulates the growth of several types of cancer’, including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer,” he explained.
A similar approach, which consists in removing immune cells in patients and “teaching” them to target cancer cells, worked in the treatment of one type of leukemia.
