HIV/AIDS: China says 14% increase in new cases
In China, a sharp increase of 14% in the number of citizens suffering from HIV and AIDS.
According to the representatives of health authorities, in total there are more than 820,000 patients in the country.
In the second quarter of 2018, 40,000 new cases were reported.
In most cases, the disease was sexually transmitted, indicating a change in the past trend.
For a long time, HIV spread rapidly through infected blood during transfusions in some regions of China.
However, health officials said during a conference held in Yunnan province, the number of people infected with HIV has fallen to almost zero.
However, compared to the previous year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China increased by 100,000.
Sexual transmission of HIV over time is a serious problem for the Chinese LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but the LGBT community is often discriminated against.
According to research, 70-90% of men who have sexual relations with other men later marry women because of the dominance of conservative values in the country.
Transmission of the disease in most cases occurs as a result of improper use of protection during sexual contact.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised to provide free access to HIV medicines, seeing this as a way to partially solve the problem.
