What is the Global Citizen Festival and how can it impact poverty reduction?
This Saturday, New York will host the Global Citizen Festival – an annual event in the music world with a staggering number of star performers and a no less exciting mission – to overcome poverty around the world.
During the seventh Global Citizen Festival, tens of thousands of people will flock to the Great Lawn of Central Park, not only to enjoy the performances of Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Sean Mendes, but also to draw attention to the true goal of the festival – the organizers strive to overcome extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, launched in 2012, is a continuation of the Global Poverty Project, an international NGO that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
To get a free ticket to the event (unless you want to pay for a VIP ticket), visitors must complete a number of tasks or “doings”, such as taking part in a volunteer project, writing an email to a world leader, making a phone call, or anything else to help draw attention to the organization’s goal of eradicating poverty.
So are there any results already, because the organizers of Global Citizen have 12 years left to achieve the goal?
Is the idea of rewarding a free concert for an act really a brilliant way to convince people to demand action, or is it just another case of so-called “clictivism” when people feel that they are really changing something by signing an e-petition or making a post on Twitter?
According to Global Citizen, since 2011, they have recorded 19 million “actions” of their supporters aimed at achieving different goals.
The organization claims that these actions prompted world leaders to announce planned financial allocations and programs worth more than $37 billion, which will help change the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group cited 390 financial commitments and public statements as an example of its performance, with at least 10 billion already collected and spent.
According to the group, the funds provided have already directly affected the lives of approximately 649 million people around the world.
Among the main financial commitments is the Foundation The Power of Nutrition, which is territorially related to the UK. As part of the project, investors and implementers undertook to "help children grow up" and promised to provide Rwanda with $ 35 million in aid to overcome the problem of malnutrition after receiving more than 4,700 messages from Global Citerti.
“With the support of the UK government, patrons, governments of other countries and citizens of the world like you, we can make the social problem of malnutrition a minor fact of history,” said Tracy Ullman, a spokeswoman for The Power of Nutrition, during a live concert in London in April 2018.
The organization also said that after 5,000 “actions” called for improving the nutrition of mothers and children, the UK government announced the allocation of funds for the project The Power of Nutrition, aimed at improving the nutrition of 5 million mothers and children.
In response to one of the common questions on your website, "Why do you think you can overcome extreme poverty?",
Global Citizen wrote: “This is a long and difficult road, so sometimes we will fall and we will fail.
However, like the civil rights and anti-apartheid movements to us, we will succeed because together we are stronger.”
Janet Jackson, The Weeknd, Sean Mendes, Cardi B, Gianella Mona are just a part of the star performers who will perform at this year’s festival in New York City, and will be hosted by Deborah-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman.
