The National Trust will observe the secret life of bats
The new study, which is being carried out on the grounds of land ownership in the Scottish Highlands, aims to establish how bats use the landscape in search of food.
The scientists hope that the data will help shed light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals in order to carry out measures for their preservation in the future.
In the gardens of Inverry in Wester Ross, scientists of the National Trust of Scotland will observe species such as bat dwarf and bat pygmy, as well as the common olfactory and watery nightshade.
Special registrars will be placed in strategic locations on the territory of land ownership to observe the behavior of bats during the season.
Employees and volunteers of the National Trust of Scotland will also conduct mobile research using hand-held detectors.
Expert analysis of all recorded sounds will help to determine the frequency and affiliation of the screams of bats.
Then it is planned to develop a detailed map of the animals’ habitat and prepare a report to link the animals’ behavior to their habitat.
Rob Dewar, a conservation adviser at the National Trust of Scotland, hopes the findings will help determine which habitats are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to assess the effectiveness of habitat care measures (e.g. meadow formation) and identify optimal methods of forest conservation for bats and other related species.
During the last century, bat populations have declined significantly in Scotland and the United Kingdom.
They are threatened by active construction and development of territories, which deprives them of nesting places.
Other negative factors include wind installations and lighting, adhesive paper for flies, chemical treatment of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not actually blind.
However, by hunting at night, the ears are more effective at catching prey than the eyes.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to detect insects and obstructions on the flight trajectory.
The National Trust of Scotland, which handles more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of special importance and 76,000 hectares of land nationwide, takes bat problems very seriously.
Ten specially trained experts regularly conduct research, inspections of nesting sites and sometimes even rescue operations.
The organization even created the first and only in Scotland reserve for bats. It is located on the territory of the Tryve estate in the region of Dumfries and Galloway. It found shelter eight out of ten species of bats living in Scotland.
The estate manager David Thompson claims that this is the perfect place for them.
"In the territory of the Tryv estate excellent conditions for bats," he assures.
"There are old buildings, many giant trees and other favorable living conditions.
However, we still need to learn a lot about bats. Thanks to the research we do here and elsewhere, we will be able to learn more about what they need to thrive.”
He insists that it is very important to check the territory for the presence of bats before carrying out any technical work, since due to the unintentional destruction of one nesting place for breeding young can kill up to 400 females with young, which is likely to cause the destruction of the entire local population.
Bats and their nests are protected by law. Animals are forbidden to kill, torture or disturb.
Elizabeth Ferrell, an officer at the Scottish Fledermaus Conservation Centre, urged the public to join the organization's efforts.
She said, "We still have a lot to learn about our bats. We still haven't revealed the characteristics of populations of many species."
