This measure neutralizes all attempts by Corbyn to attract young voters
Higher state duty will be levied on those who do not pay taxes in the UK
The Ministry of Finance hopes to raise an additional 120 million pounds per year to help the homeless
As Theresa May announced today, foreigners buying real estate in the UK will pay more tax. Additional funds will be spent on helping the homeless.
The move could be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s efforts to attract young voters with promises of more affordable housing aimed at high-paying workers.
The tariff increase will apply to individuals and legal entities that do not pay taxes in the UK. The government will allocate additional funds to help those who are forced to spend the night in the open air.
The additional duty, which accompanies the increase of two years of antiquity on the second housing and real estate intended for rent, may be three percent.
The Ministry of Finance expects to attract an additional 120 million pounds per year.
According to experts, 13% of new real estate, which is being built in London, falls into the property of foreign citizens. This leads to higher prices and complicates the task for those who only dream about their own housing.
Many wealthy areas of the country, in particular, in the capital, are empty, since a large number of foreign buyers most of the time live outside the country.
The new action plan came just weeks after Boris Johnson called for lowering state duties to make housing more accessible to young people.
He accused major construction companies of maintaining high real estate prices by buying up land without further use. He urged Theresa May to abandon quotas for affordable real estate in order to correct the "disgraceful situation in the housing market" in the UK.
Mr. Corbyn announced a number of important real estate reforms, including rent control and the impossibility of eviction without good reason.
He also proposes to expand the powers of local councils in the field of construction of new housing.
Theresa May said: “I promised last year that I would dedicate my premiere to restoring the British dream – for every new generation, life should be better.
This requires changes in our imperfect housing market.
The UK will always remain open to those who want to live, work and build their future here.
However, it cannot be called fair that individuals who do not live in the UK, as well as foreign companies, buy housing on the same terms as British citizens.
For too many people, the dream of their own home has become unattainable. The problem of living in the open air is still very painful."
