Four real mothers dance in a hay-filled barn to a song containing the words: "Yes, I feed myself, but I do not have a tail" and "As you can see, it is not the udder, but my breasts."
Then the choir sings: "Suck, suck, to feed the children. Suck, suck, so that the milk is not wasted."
However, an advertisement posted on the company’s Facebook page sparked a heated discussion online.
The video received 77,000 views and hundreds of comments. However, the reaction of Internet users was ambiguous. Many noted that the advertising underestimated the "terrible organization" of milk production in the industry.
“It’s not a very smart decision to use cows to advertise this product.
Like us, they need to get pregnant and give birth to give milk. However, their children are vilely taken away from them a few days after birth,” one user wrote.
The Elvie milk extractor can be easily hidden in a feeding bra (Elvie/Mother)
Here is another comment: "It is clear that this is traumatic for both the mother and the child.
But why not engage them to advertise a milk suction cup for women who need to feed their babies?”
Someone else added: "This advertisement is very far from reality."
Other users defended the ad. One of the women video seemed "very funny".
“I think it’s a brilliant idea.
I would certainly have bought such a thing if I were still breastfeeding.
By sucking the milk, I felt like a cow.
The advertising is a bit crazy, but I did not look for hidden content in it.
It’s a great product,” someone wrote.
Here’s another comment: “Funny advertising focused on moms who suck milk (often in the workplace or in the toilet) and feel like cows.
This advertising is not aimed at highlighting the advantages and disadvantages of the dairy industry."
At the end of the video, women show milk suction cups hidden in their bras.
The concept of an advertising campaign is based on information that many women who use similar products feel like cows.
However, the suction cup Elvie works absolutely silently, has no wires or tubes and easily hides in a feeding bra. Thanks to this, women can move freely, keep children and even go outside.
Ana Balarin, partner and executive creative director of the advertising agency Mother, commented on the situation: “The Elvie suction cup is such a revolutionary product that it required a bright and provocative presentation.
Drawing a parallel between milk-squeezing women and real cows, we wanted to draw attention to the features of breastfeeding, in an exciting and interesting way demonstrating the incredible sense of freedom that a new suction cup would bring.
The suction cup Elvie is not the first time in the headlines.
As part of Fashion Week in London, the mother of two children appeared on the catwalk with this product during the show of clothes from fashion designer Marta Jakubovska.
