Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people were killed in a powerful earthquake and tsunami in the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, government officials said, but the death toll could rise.
Due to the failure of communications, officials dealing with humanitarian aid issues cannot obtain any information from the Regency of Dongala, an area north of Palu that is closer to the epicenter of the 7.5-magnitude earthquake.
After the disaster, 16,000 people were evacuated from Palu.
Here are some basic facts about the city of Palu and the Regency of Dongala, located on the island of Sulawesi.
Palu is the capital of Central Sulawesi Province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 according to data for 2017.
When there was an earthquake that caused a tsunami, the city celebrated its 40th anniversary.
Dongala is a regency that stretches for more than 300 km (180 mi) along the coastline in the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
According to data for 2017, the regency, an administrative region located in the lower part of the province, has about 299,200 people.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main economic sectors of Central Sulawesi Province, especially the coastal region of Dongala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but is mainly concentrated in Morovala, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
According to the Indonesian disaster alleviation agency, Palu and Dongala have been affected by the tsunami several times over the past 100 years.
In 1938, the tsunami in Dongala killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes.
In 1996, the tsunami also covered the western part of Donggal, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in a seismically active Pacific Ring of Fire and regularly suffers from earthquakes.
Below are some of the largest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years.
2004: On December 26, a severe earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh, located in the north of Sumatra, caused a tsunami that struck 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh province.
2005: In late March and early April, a series of powerful earthquakes struck the west coast of Sumatra.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A magnitude 6.8 earthquake rocked southern Java, Indonesia's most densely populated island, and caused a tsunami that hit the southern coast, killing about 700 people.
2009: Near the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra, recorded an earthquake of magnitude 7.6.
More than 1,100 people died.
2010: A 7.5-magnitude earthquake rocked one of the Mentawai islands near Sumatra, causing a tsunami up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A weak earthquake hits the Pidjaya Regency in Aceh province, causing destruction and panic due to the fact that people have not yet forgotten the devastating earthquake and tsunami of 2004.
This time there was no tsunami, but more than 100 people died under the rubble of buildings.
2018: Strong earthquakes hit the tourist island of Lombok in Indonesia, killing more than 500 people, mostly in the northern part of the island.
The earthquake destroyed many houses, and thousands of tourists could not leave the island at once.
