Five of the dead were tourists from Argentina.
It has been ten years since the Southern District of New York last opened a criminal case that is punishable by the death penalty.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of murdering two drug suppliers and was eventually sentenced to life in prison in September 2009.
The last time the death penalty in a federal case was carried out in New York in 1953, the couple Julius and Ethel Rosenberg were executed after being convicted of conspiracy to spy on the Soviet Union during the Cold War two years earlier.
Both Rosenbergs were executed on an electric chair on June 19, 1953.
According to court materials, Saipov, a native of Uzbekistan, did not show remorse in the days and months following the attack.
